<HL>
   AT&amp;T, Unions
   Reach Agreement
   On Retirements
   ----
   By John J. Keller
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/16/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B5
</SO>
<CO>
   T LABOR
</CO>
<IN>
TELEPHONE SYSTEMS (TLS)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. and its
unions agreed on a non-management retirement plan that would
raise the number of eligible workers to 33,500 from 18,000,
keeping the company's work force-reduction plans on track.
   AT&amp;T says it won't be able to assess the financial impact
of the accord until it knows how many workers will take
advantage of it.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The agreement, which had been expected, also empowers
individual AT&amp;T units to offer additional incentives to the
new plan to encourage workers in superfluous jobs to leave
without sacrificing their early retirement benefits.
   "Unions tend to be one-size fits all, and this allows
individual units to respond better to their own business
conditions," said an AT&amp;T spokesman. For example, AT&amp;T's
Network Services division will cut 6,000 surplus jobs because
it doesn't need as many people to maintain a phone network
that has been upgraded to more modern digital equipment.
   AT&amp;T had said that it would have to lay off the workers
without full early retirement benefits if it didn't receive
an agreement on the special incentives from the unions -- the
Communications Workers of America and the International
Brotherhood of Electrical Workers.
   The new plan adds three years of age and three years of
service to the records of all non-management employees as of
May 1. These added years accelerate eligibility and increase
the pension payout to each worker.
   In addition, individual units with a surplus of workers
will be able to offer an incentive of two additional years of
age and two more years of seniority for workers. The units
can also offer a "sweetener" that raises monthly pension
payments 15% a month.
   All told, AT&amp;T has firm plans this year to consolidate
numerous office and manufacturing sites and to cut 12,800
non-management jobs. The company currently has 165,400
non-managers out of 281,000 workers. That is about 92,000
fewer workers than in January 1984 when AT&amp;T was broken up
and 28,000 less than AT&amp;T had 17 months ago.
</TEXT>
