<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media:
   CBS Posts Ratings Victory
   In Prime-Time Viewing
</HL>
<DATE>
05/16/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B5
</SO>
<CO>
   GE CBS CCB
</CO>
<IN>
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- CBS won the prime-time ratings last week for
the first time since June 1988.
   According to the A.C. Nielsen Co., CBS Inc.'s TV network
finished first with 11.7% of the audience, followed by NBC, a
unit of General Electric Co., with 11.5% and ABC, a division
of Capital Cities/ABC Inc., with 11%. Nielsen is a unit of
New York-based Dun &amp; Bradstreet Corp.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   CBS's victory was attributed to its strong ratings on
Sunday, with "60 Minutes" and "Shattered Dreams" a
made-for-TV movie, and on Monday with two hours of comedies
and a one-hour special hosted by Connie Chung.
   ABC had the top three shows, including "America's Funniest
Home Videos," which was No. 1. A companion show, "America's
Funniest . . . Part II" was rated No. 3. "Roseanne" was No.
2.
   CBS also had the lowest-rated show, the Saturday night
comedy series, "City," which attracted only 3.3% of the
viewers. That was the lowest-rated network show in history
tying "Live From Studio 8H" on NBC in January 1982.
</TEXT>
