<HL>
   International:
   Degussa and E. Merck End
   Plan for Merging Divisions
</HL>
<DATE>
05/16/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A16
</SO>
<CO>
   G.DGS
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   FRANKFURT, West Germany -- Degussa AG and E. Merck said
they have abandoned their plan to merge their pharmaceutical
divisions, citing a lack of common interests.
   The two West German chemicals groups said a study by a
joint expert commission has shown that "the common interests
for a cooperation weren't sufficient."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "The talks were subsequently terminated," Degussa and
Merck said in a statement.
   In late 1989, Degussa approached Merck with the proposal
to merge its Asta Pharma AG drug subsidiary with the much
larger pharmaceutical division of Merck and take a minority
stake in the joint venture.
   Merck, which is closely held, isn't affiliated with Merck
&amp; Co. of the U.S.
   Details on the talks were first disclosed in February, and
at a news conference in March, Degussa Chairman Gert Becker
still expressed optimism that the negotations would succeed.
   But Hans-Werner Hauck, Merck's finance chief, said the
concept proposed by Degussa wasn't in the best interest of
Merck. "Degussa wanted to sell its division and still have a
say in it, but this is a difficult construction," he said.
   A Degussa spokesman declined to give any reasons for the
failure of the talks.
</TEXT>
