<HL>
   Consumer Prices Rose in March
</HL>
<DATE>
05/16/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   FORGN
</CO>
<LP>
   PARIS -- Consumer prices among the world's industrial
countries rose an average 0.7% in March after a 0.6% increase
in February, despite slower growth in food prices and
declining energy costs, the Organization for Economic
Cooperation and Development said.
   For the 12 months to March, OECD consumer prices rose
6.5%, up from February's year-on-year rise of 6.4%.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The organization said food prices grew 0.4% in the latest
reporting month compared with a 0.9% gain in February.
   Meanwhile, March energy prices fell 0.2% after declining
0.5% in February.
   The "underlying" inflation rate, excluding food and energy
costs, edged up to 0.6% from 0.5%. The underlying rate during
the 12 months to March was 4.7%, up from 4.5% in February.
</TEXT>
