<HL>
   Heard on the Street:
   Warning Flag Is Raised as Stock Market Hits New High
   ----
   By Roger Lowenstein
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/16/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C1
</SO>
<CO>
   JAPAN
</CO>
<IN>
HEARD ON THE STREET (HRD)
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- As the Standard &amp; Poor's 500-stock index has
surged to a multiple of 16.3 times earnings, Wall Street has
had an explanation for it all.
   The reason stock prices have been climbing while earnings
have been falling, analysts say, is that interest rates have
also gone into a swoon.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   But according to one significant yardstick that compares
stock multiples with interest rates, the S&amp;P 500 is more
expensive now than at any time since before the October 1987
crash.
   "Relative to the bond market, stock prices look 15% to 20%
overpriced," says Leon G. Cooperman, chairman of Goldman
Sachs Asset Management.
   Despite the recent bond rally, yields on government bonds
are up considerably -- more than 0.6 of a percentage point --
since year-end. All things being equal, that should warrant
lower stock prices. But the S&amp;P 500 index is up marginally
from its year end close of 353.4.
   "In my view, bonds represent a very good alternative to
equities," says Abby Joseph Cohen, the chief strategist for
Barclays de Zoete Wedd, the brokerage arm of Barclays Bank.
   A good proxy for the relative worth of stocks and bonds is
what Salomon Brothers terms the "earnings/yield gap." The
term sounds arcane, but the concept is basic.
   The earnings yield on stocks is the return (defined as the
annual corporate earnings) divided by the share price. If a
company earning $1 a share sells for $100, the yield to
investors, whether paid out in dividends or kept as retained
earnings, is 1%. (The earnings yield is also equal to one
divided by the price/earnings multiple.)
   The earnings/yield gap is obtained by starting with the
rate prevailing on 10-year government bonds and subtracting
the earnings yield of the S&amp;P 500 stocks. Right now, this gap
amounts to 2.48 percentage points.
   In other words, the 8.6% interest that investors can
collect on 10-year government bonds is almost 2.5 percentage
points higher than the earnings yield on stocks. Today's gap
is still far narrower than the precrash extreme of 4.67
percentage points. Yet it is wider than at any time since
just before Black Monday.
   Michael Belkin, the Salomon analyst who tracks the yield
gap, says "it's probably the best `quick and dirty' measure
of the relationship between stock prices and interest rates."
   When the yield gap widens, it signals that stocks,
relative to the risk-free returns available in the government
bond market, are becoming pricier. Bargain-priced stocks are
more likely to be found when the gap is narrow.
   In the bear market of the 1970s, the yield gap was often
negative -- meaning that bonds were yielding less than
stocks. In the early 1980s, a period of double-digit interest
rates, the gap briefly widened to more than four percentage
points. It narrowed in the mid-1980s, and then roared to a
record high just before Black Monday.
   "If the gap is too large compared to its historical range,
it probably means that stocks are vulnerable," Mr. Belkin
says, adding: "Stock prices can't shrug off interest rates
forever."
   But Mr. Belkin isn't among those who believe that the gap
today is so large as to suggest that stocks are overvalued.
Looking back to the early 1980s, he says the gap is well
within its historical range.
   Japan's stock market, despite its recent slide, is more
expensive than the U.S. market, Mr. Belkin adds. In fact, by
this measure, he says, Japanese stocks are more overvalued
than they were at year end -- when prices were 20% higher --
because interest rates in Japan also have risen.
   "Even with the recent stock market slide, Japanese stocks
don't reflect the rise in Japanese interest rates," Mr.
Belkin says. The yield gap in Japan is 5.02%, compared with
4.22% at year end.
   Stock market savants say it's indisputable that, at some
level, a rising yield gap spells trouble. The hard part?
Determining when.
   "The problem is, you're taking a snapshot at one instant
in time," says George Michaelis, president of First Pacific
Advisers. "Stocks have earnings growth, and interest rates
can be very volatile." In the early 1980s, he says, a large
yield gap obscured the fact -- observable in retrospect --
that stocks held "tremendous value."
   Charles Clough, chief investment strategist at Merrill
Lynch, agrees that stocks are overvalued relative to bonds
but, he adds: "Over the past 20 years the normal boundary has
been rising. It has taken higher values of overvaluation to
stop the market."
   Investors, he says, have become more optimistic about
earnings growth as the economic expansion has continued --
pushing up price/earnings multiples and also such measures as
the yield gap. Thus, to some extent, the yield gap can be
considered a measure of investors' expectations for earnings
growth.
   Investors are still sanguine, Mr. Clough says dryly, "even
though there is no sign of an earnings bottom." Dillon Read
research chief Joseph McAlinden says stocks aren't overvalued
relative to bonds, because he expects corporate earnings to
rise.
   Goldman's Mr. Cooperman, computes what he says is a more
dynamic version of the yield gap. Mr. Cooperman's model
factors in a "risk premium" for owning stocks and assumes
that, over the long haul, corporate earnings will grow 7% a
year.
   He also concludes that, relative to bonds, stocks are
overvalued. Over time, Mr. Cooperman says the balance between
markets should be rectified in one of three ways. He expects
"a drop in stock prices, a further decline in interest rates,
or the passage of time, allowing earnings to catch up."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900516-0033
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900516-0033.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Technology &amp; Health:
   Sun Introduces
   Its PC-Priced
   Workstation
   ----
   By G. Pascal Zachary
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/16/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   SUNW
</CO>
<IN>
COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)
</IN>
<LP>
   MOUNTAIN VIEW, Calif. -- Sun Microsystems Inc. introduced
a computer workstation priced at $4,995, setting a new
standard for high-powered desktop computing at relatively low
prices.
   Sun's new computer, called the Sparcstation SLC, is likely
to cement Sun's lead in the workstation market, one of the
fastest-growing segments of the computer industry. While
Sun's chief competitors in workstations, Hewlett-Packard Inc.
and Digital Equipment Corp., vow to introduce similarly
priced but more powerful workstations, some analysts think
Sun's new machine will confound competitors for many months.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "This makes it difficult for DEC and HP to keep up with
Sun in the workstation business," said Vicki Brown, an
analysts at International Data Corp.
   Sun declined to estimate future sales of the machine,
though it said it had already received orders for 5,000
units.
   However, Ms. Brown said Sun's newest computer is expected
to lift sales of its year-old Sparcstation family
significantly. She said sales of all three models, including
the SLC, will probably total 95,000 units this year, roughly
three times last year's sales.
   Besides helping Sun satisfy its traditional engineering
and scientific customers, the new machine will add momentum
to the company's assault on the market for personal
computers, generally used by white collar workers.
   "The battle today is on the desktop," said Scott McNealy,
Sun's chief executive officer, referring to the company's
plans to butt heads with such PC makers as Apple Computer
Inc.
   While Sun may steal some PC sales, the new SLC lacks a
hard-disk drive, the basic storage device for PCs, and it
can't be upgraded with accessories that improve performance.
   But the machine operates at blazing speeds -- 12.5 million
operations a second -- because it has at its heart Sun's own
Sparc microprocessor. The extra speed is useful in, for
instance, financial modeling or electronic publishing, where
PCs often lack the horsepower to carry out complex tasks.
   Sun is expected to introduce an even faster Sparcstation
before the end of the year, putting further pressure on
competitors. That machine might even share the same packaging
as the SLC, which is designed so that its circuitry shares
the same housing as its 17-inch monitor.
   The packaging is crucial to Sun's profit margins on the
computer, which may sell for as little as $3,000 when
purchased in large quantities. Ms. Brown said Sun spent $1
million on tooling for the computer and managed to design the
machine without a fan, which reduces the computer's noise and
manufacturing costs.
   In national over-the-counter trading yesterday, Sun shares
closed at $29.25 apiece, down $1.25 on heavy volume of about
1.9 million shares.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900516-0032
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900516-0032.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   MCEG Sets Revamp
   Of Loan From Kidder
   In Exchange for Stake
</HL>
<DATE>
05/16/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   MCEG GE
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   LOS ANGELES -- Management Co. Entertainment Group Inc.
said it agreed in principle with Kidder, Peabody Group Inc.
for the General Electric Co. unit to restructure its $72.5
million bridge loan in exchange for as much as a 28% stake in
MCEG, a financially troubled motion-picture producer and
distributor.
   MCEG said Kidder agreed to replace the loan MCEG used to
acquire Virgin Vision Ltd. last August with $55 million of
two-year notes and $17.5 million of five-year notes. The loan
was initially due May 29.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In return, MCEG will issue warrants or convertible bonds
to Kidder, allowing the New York investment banking firm to
buy 12 million of its common shares for $3 each. MCEG said
Kidder will receive warrants to purchase an additional eight
million shares at $3 each if the company hasn't repaid the
five-year notes by Dec. 31.
   The arrangement could give Kidder a stake of as much as
28% in the company, MCEG said, assuming it had 64 million
shares outstanding at year end on a fully diluted basis.
   The financing arrangement is subject to a number of
significant conditions, including approval by MCEG's board.
   MCEG shares were quoted at $2.8125, bid, in
over-the-counter trading yesterday.
</TEXT>
