<HL>
   Business Brief -- Trans World Airlines:
   Loss Widened Significantly
   During the First Quarter
</HL>
<DATE>
05/16/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B5
</SO>
<CO>
   TWA
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   Trans World Airlines reported a first-quarter net loss of
$143 million, significantly wider than the $83.1 million net
loss a year earlier.
   The financially troubled company, which Chairman Carl
Icahn took private in 1988, said that revenue rose 2.5% to
$1.01 billion from $989.7 million a year earlier.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   It said operating expenses rose more sharply. Costs rose
by 9.3% to $1.1 billion from $1.02 billion during the
year-earlier quarter.
   The Mount Kisco, N.Y., company attributed most of the jump
to a 35.7% rise in the price of jet fuel. It said the average
jet fuel price rose to 73.7 cents a gallon from 54.3 cents a
gallon during the first quarter of 1989. TWA said the
increase cost the company an additional $52.9 million in fuel
expenses compared with the year-earlier period.
   It said the remaining $41.9 million jump in expenses was
related to increased capacity and service changes.
