<HL>
   What's News --
   Business and finance
</HL>
<DATE>
05/16/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   THE BUDGET DEFICIT is now expected to reach $128 billion
to $140 billion for fiscal 1991, even if the cost of the
thrift bailout is excluded, the White House said. The latest
forecast, which came as Bush opened deficit talks with
congressional leaders, suggests negotiators need to find up
to $66 billion to avoid automatic spending cuts under
Gramm-Rudman.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Circle K filed for Chapter 11 protection after failing to
get creditor agreement on a debt restructuring. The nation's
No. 2 convenience store chain said it is trying to get vendor
cooperation to keep stores stocked.
   ---
   A key bank-regulatory policy was struck down by a federal
appeals court, which said the Fed doesn't have the power to
force bank holding companies to help ailing units. The case
involved Dallas-based MCorp.
   ---
   First Executive said it paid over $1.33 billion in the
first quarter to holders surrending insurance policies and
annuities, creating a vast cash outflow for the Los
Angeles-based insurance holding company. But officials said
the pace of policy surrenders slowed sharply this quarter.
   ---
   The Justice Department is pushing a bill to expand
prosecutors' ability to freeze assets of defendants in fraud
cases before trial and permanently seize their assets after
conviction.
   ---
   Manville's trust fund for asbestos victims came under fire
as two judges ordered the trust to account for a huge
shortfall in funds. The judges also indicated they may order
the fund to pay damages more quickly.
   ---
   Perkin-Elmer sold to a U.S. group a
semiconductor-equipment unit that was the focus of concerns
about Japanese inroads in the chip market.
   ---
   Blue-chip stocks edged higher, pushing the the Dow Jones
industrials up 0.92, to a record 2822.45. But the broader
market declined due to profittaking. Bonds fell modestly,
while the dollar was mixed.
   ---
   Former law partners of the defunct firm of Finley Kumble
can be sued by a bankruptcy trustee over debt payments, a
judge ruled.
   ---
   Industrial output fell 0.4% in April, reflecting a sharp
drop in the auto industry and declines in most other sectors.
Factories, utilities and mines operated at 83% of capacity,
off from 83.5% in March. The reports were a further sign the
economy is weak.
                                                                                                       

   Car and truck sales fell 8.4% in early May, damping hopes
the industry's year-long slump will end soon. Many dealers
have cut new-car orders amid uncertainty that sales will
start to rebound anytime soon.
   ---
   Manufacturers Hanover's head of investment banking,
Douglas Ebert, resigned after failing to win the top spot in
a newly combined commercial and investment banking unit.
   ---
   Nobel Industries agreed to acquire Spectra-Physics, a
major U.S. producer of lasers, from Ciba-Geigy for an
estimated $325 million.
   ---
   Corn futures prices declined on unfounded rumors about a
worsening political upheaval in the Soviet Union, a major
grain buyer, and broad selling by commodity fund managers.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 165,730,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2822.45, up 0.92; transportation 1177.10, off 3.55; utilities
217.24, up 0.12.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3347.40, off
8.75.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 133.19, off 0.32;
spot index 134.95, off 0.47.
   Dollar: 150.80 yen, off 1.67; 1.6465 marks, up 0.0040.
